<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="84" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="84">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="84">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Thorell" baseAuthorityYear="1875" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Hogna" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hogna heeri" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heeri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">Hogna heeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in montane grasslands or 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Erica" order="Ericales" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">Erica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shrubland in Madeira and the steep, semi-arid summit of Bugio.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="84" type="conservation status">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="84">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="84">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Thorell" baseAuthorityYear="1875" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Hogna" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hogna heeri" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heeri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">Hogna heeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was assessed according to the IUCN Red List criteria, with the status of Least Concern (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2018-2.RLTS.T58048559A58061002.en" author="Cardoso, P" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Ecology" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" refId="B16" refString="Cardoso, P, Crespo, LC, Silva, I, Borges, P, Boieiro, M, 2018b. Hogna heeri. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2018: 8. https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2018-2.RLTS.T58048559A58061002.en" title="Hogna heeri. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2018: 8." url="https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2018-2.RLTS.T58048559A58061002.en" year="2018 b">Cardoso et al 2018b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="84" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="84">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="84">
The specific epithet of 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. heeri" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heeri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">H. heeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been one of the names renamed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Bonnet, P" journalOrPublisher="Douladoure, Toulouse" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" refId="B8" refString="Bonnet, P, 1959. Bibliographia araneorum. Analyse methodique de toute la litterature araneologique jusqu'en 1939. Tome II. Systematique des araignees (Etude par ordre alphabetique) (5eme partie: T-Z). Douladoure, Toulouse, 4231-5058." title="Bibliographia araneorum. Analyse methodique de toute la litterature araneologique jusqu'en 1939. Tome II. Systematique des araignees (Etude par ordre alphabetique) (5 eme partie: T-Z). Douladoure, Toulouse, 4231 - 5058." year="1959">Bonnet (1959)</bibRefCitation>
, who changed all previously described spider 
<normalizedToken originalValue="species’">species'</normalizedToken>
names which were patronyms ending in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“ii”">&quot;ii&quot;</normalizedToken>
to end in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“i”">&quot;i&quot;</normalizedToken>
, as a way to correct spelling (
<bibRefCitation author="Bonnet, P" journalOrPublisher="Douladoure, Toulouse" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" refId="B7" refString="Bonnet, P, 1945. Bibliographia araneorum. Analyse methodique de toute la litterature araneologique jusqu'en 1939. Tome I. Douladoure, Toulouse" title="Bibliographia araneorum. Analyse methodique de toute la litterature araneologique jusqu'en 1939. Tome I." year="1945">Bonnet 1945</bibRefCitation>
). Although the ICZN argues for the maintenance of the original spelling, common usage dictates that these modified spellings continue to be used. The disjunct distribution of 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. heeri" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heeri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">H. heeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with populations in Madeira and Bugio, is somewhat baffling. The only known specimens from Bugio previously reported (
<bibRefCitation author="Crespo, L" journalOrPublisher="Revista Iberica de Aracnologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" pagination="11 - 23" refId="B24" refString="Crespo, L, Silva, I, Borges, P, Cardoso, P, 2013. Rapid biodiversity assessment, faunistics and description of a new spider species (Araneae) from Desertas Islands and Madeira (Portugal). Revista Iberica de Aracnologia 23: 11 - 23" title="Rapid biodiversity assessment, faunistics and description of a new spider species (Araneae) from Desertas Islands and Madeira (Portugal)." volume="23" year="2013">Crespo et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
) were examined: while the female matches 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. heeri" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heeri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">H. heeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the male pedipalp is the same as that of 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. isambertoi" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="isambertoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">H. isambertoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., with the tip of the embolus slightly tilted anteriorly (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Hogna isambertoi sp. nov. A-C male (SMF): A left male palp, ventral B detail of the median apophysis, anteroventral C SEM image, right male palp, ventral D, E female (SMF): D epigynum, ventral E vulva, dorsal. Abbreviations, male palp: C - cymbium, E - embolus, MA - median apophysis, P - palea, T - tegulum, TA - terminal apophysis. Abbreviations, female genitalia: D - diverticulum, H - epigynal hoods, MS - median septum, S - spermatheca. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A); 0.2 mm (B-E)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1086.68015.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/646998" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">18A</figureCitation>
). We would like to remark that Wunderlich reported an apophysis at the base of the embolus (indicated with an arrow in his figure) as a diagnostic feature to identify males of 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. heeri" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heeri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">H. heeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Wunderlich, J" journalOrPublisher="Beitraege zur Araneologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" pagination="1 - 619" refId="B76" refString="Wunderlich, J, 1992. Die Spinnen-Fauna der Makaronesischen Inseln: Taxonomie, Oekologie, Biogeographie und Evolution. Beitraege zur Araneologie 1: 1 - 619" title="Die Spinnen-Fauna der Makaronesischen Inseln: Taxonomie, Oekologie, Biogeographie und Evolution." volume="1" year="1992">Wunderlich 1992</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 720), which appears to be either inconspicuous or missing altogether. To us it seems the arrow is pointing to the pars pendula membrane connecting the terminal apophysis with the embolus. Unfortunately, we could not gather molecular information from the Bugio specimens due to their poor preservation. Lastly, while revising 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Thorell’s">Thorell's</normalizedToken>
type series, we identified one of the three adult females in the original vial as 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. insularum" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insularum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="84">H. insularum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
